	abstract = {We present high-resolution \$K\$-band emission spectra of the quintessential hot Jupiter HD 189733 b from the Keck Planet Imager and Characterizer (KPIC). Using a Bayesian retrieval framework, we fit the dayside pressure-temperature profile, orbital kinematics, mass-mixing ratios of H\$\_2\$O, CO, CH\$\_4\$, NH\$\_3\$, HCN, and H\$\_2\$S, and the \${\textbackslash}rm {\textasciicircum}\{13\}CO/{\textasciicircum}\{12\}CO\$ ratio. We measure mass fractions of \${\textbackslash}rm {\textbackslash}log H\_2O = -2.0{\textasciicircum}\{+0.4\}\_\{-0.4\}\$ and \${\textbackslash}rm {\textbackslash}log CO = -2.2{\textasciicircum}\{+0.5\}\_\{-0.5\}\$, and place upper limits on the remaining species. Notably, we find \${\textbackslash}rm {\textbackslash}log CH\_4 {\textless} -4.5\$ at 99{\textbackslash}\% confidence, despite its anticipated presence at the equilibrium temperature of HD 189733 b assuming local thermal equilibrium. We make a tentative (\${\textbackslash}sim3{\textbackslash}sigma\$) detection of \${\textbackslash}rm {\textasciicircum}\{13\}CO\$, and the retrieved posteriors suggest a \${\textbackslash}rm {\textasciicircum}\{12\}C/{\textasciicircum}\{13\}C\$ ratio similar to or substantially less than the local interstellar value. The possible \${\textbackslash}rm {\textasciicircum}\{13\}C\$ enrichment would be consistent with accretion of fractionated material in ices or in the protoplanetary disk midplane. The retrieved abundances correspond to a substantially sub-stellar atmospheric \${\textbackslash}rm C/O = 0.3{\textbackslash}pm0.1\$, while the carbon and oxygen abundances are stellar to slightly super-stellar, consistent with core-accretion models which predict an inverse correlation between C/O and metallicity. The specific combination of low C/O and high metallicity suggests significant accretion of solid material may have occurred late in the formation process of HD 189733 b.},
