	shorttitle = {The {Hubble} {PanCET} {Program}},
	url = {https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.3847/1538-3881/ac58fc},
	doi = {10.3847/1538-3881/ac58fc},
	abstract = {We present the most complete emission spectrum for inﬂated hot Jupiter HAT-P-41b combining new Hubble Space Telescope Wide Field Camera/G141 spectrum from the Hubble Panchromatic Comparative Exoplanet Treasury program with archival Spitzer eclipse observations. We found a near blackbody-like emission spectrum, which is best ﬁtted with an isothermal temperature–pressure (TP) proﬁle, that agrees well with the dayside heat redistribution scenario assuming zero Bond albedo. The noninverted TP proﬁle is consistent with the nondetection of near-UV/optical absorbers in the transit spectra. We do not ﬁnd any evidence for signiﬁcant H− opacity nor a metal-rich atmosphere. HAT-P-41b is an ideal target that sits in the transitioning parameter space between hot and ultra-hot Jupiters, and future James Webb Space Telescope observations will help us to better constrain the thermal structure and chemical composition.},
