	abstract = {We present a comprehensive analysis of the 0.3--5{\textbackslash},\${\textbackslash}mu\$m transit spectrum for the inflated hot Jupiter HAT-P-41b. The planet was observed in transit with Hubble STIS and WFC3 as part of the Hubble Panchromatic Comparative Exoplanet Treasury (PanCET) program, and we combine those data with warm {\textbackslash}textit\{Spitzer\} transit observations. We extract transit depths from each of the data sets, presenting the STIS transit spectrum (0.29--0.93{\textbackslash},\${\textbackslash}mu\$m) for the first time. We retrieve the transit spectrum both with a free-chemistry retrieval suite (AURA) and a complementary chemical equilibrium retrieval suite (PLATON) to constrain the atmospheric properties at the day-night terminator. Both methods provide an excellent fit to the observed spectrum. Both AURA and PLATON retrieve a metal-rich atmosphere for almost all model assumptions (most likely O/H ratio of \${\textbackslash}log\_\{10\}\{Z/Z\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\} = 1.46{\textasciicircum}\{+0.53\}\_\{-0.68\}\$ and \${\textbackslash}log\_\{10\}\{Z/Z\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\} = 2.33{\textasciicircum}\{+0.23\}\_\{-0.25\}\$, respectively); this is driven by a 4.9-\${\textbackslash}sigma\$ detection of H\$\_2\$O as well as evidence of gas absorption in the optical (\${\textgreater}\$2.7-\${\textbackslash}sigma\$ detection) due to Na, AlO and/or VO/TiO, though no individual species is strongly detected. Both retrievals determine the transit spectrum to be consistent with a clear atmosphere, with no evidence of haze or high-altitude clouds. Interior modeling constraints on the maximum atmospheric metallicity (\${\textbackslash}log\_\{10\}\{Z/Z\_\{{\textbackslash}odot\}\} {\textless} 1.7\$) favor the AURA results. The inferred elemental oxygen abundance suggests that HAT-P-41b has one of the most metal-rich atmospheres of any hot Jupiters known to date. Overall, the inferred high metallicity and high inflation make HAT-P-41b an interesting test case for planet formation theories.},
	number = {2},
